# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cedar-policy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] In computer security, an **access-control list** (**ACL**) is a list of permissions associated with a system resource (object or facility).
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] An ACL specifies which users or system processes are granted access to resources, as well as what operations are allowed on given resources.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Each entry in a typical ACL specifies a subject and an operation.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Many kinds of operating systems implement ACLs or have a historical implementation; the first implementation of ACLs was in the filesystem of Multics in 1965.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] A filesystem ACL is a data structure (usually a table) containing entries that specify individual user or group rights to specific system objects such as programs, processes, or files.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] These entries are known as access-control entries (ACEs) in the Microsoft Windows NT, OpenVMS, and Unix-like operating systems such as Linux, macOS, and Solaris.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Each accessible object contains an identifier to its ACL.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] The privileges or permissions determine specific access rights, such as whether a user can read from, write to, or execute an object.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] In some implementations, an ACE can control whether or not a user, or group of users, may alter the ACL on an object.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] One of the first operating systems to provide filesystem ACLs was Multics.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] PRIMOS featured ACLs at least as early as 1984.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] In the 1990s the ACL and role-based access control (RBAC) models were extensively tested and used to administer file permissions.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] POSIX 1003.1e/1003.2c working group made an effort to standardize ACLs, resulting in what is now known as "POSIX.1e ACL" or simply "POSIX ACL".
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] The POSIX.1e/POSIX.2c drafts were withdrawn in 1997 due to participants losing interest for funding the project and turning to more powerful alternatives such as NFSv4 ACLs.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] As of December 2019, no live sources of the draft could be found on the Internet, but it can still be found in the Internet Archive.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Most of the Unix and Unix-like operating systems (e.g.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Linux since 2.5.46 or November 2002, FreeBSD, or Solaris) support POSIX.1e ACLs (not necessarily draft 17).
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] ACLs are usually stored in the extended attributes of a file on these systems.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are much more powerful than POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Unlike draft POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are defined by a published standard, as part of the Network File System.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are supported by many Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Examples include AIX, FreeBSD, Mac OS X beginning with version 10.4 ("Tiger"), or Solaris with ZFS filesystem, support NFSv4 ACLs, which are part of the NFSv4 standard.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] There are two experimental implementations of NFSv4 ACLs for Linux: NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext3 filesystem and the more recent Richacls, which brings NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext4 filesystem.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] As with POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are usually stored as extended attributes on Unix-like systems.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are organized nearly identically to the Windows NT ACLs used in NTFS.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4.1 ACLs are a superset of both NT ACLs and POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Samba supports saving the NT ACLs of SMB-shared files in many ways, one of which is as NFSv4-encoded ACLs.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Microsoft's Active Directory service implements an LDAP server that stores and disseminates configuration information about users and computers in a domain.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Active Directory extends the LDAP specification by adding the same type of access-control list mechanism as Windows NT uses for the NTFS filesystem.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Windows 2000 then extended the syntax for access-control entries such that they could not only grant or deny access to entire LDAP objects, but also to individual attributes within these objects.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] On some types of proprietary computer hardware (in particular, routers and switches), an access-control list provides rules that are applied to port numbers or IP addresses that are available on a host or other layer 3, each with a list of hosts and/or networks permitted to use the service.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Although it is additionally possible to configure access-control lists based on network domain names, this is a questionable idea because individual TCP, UDP, and ICMP headers do not contain domain names.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Consequently, the device enforcing the access-control list must separately resolve names to numeric addresses.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] This presents an additional attack surface for an attacker who is seeking to compromise security of the system which the access-control list is protecting.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Both individual servers and routers can have network ACLs.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Access-control lists can generally be configured to control both inbound and outbound traffic, and in this context they are similar to firewalls.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Like firewalls, ACLs could be subject to security regulations and standards such as PCI DSS.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] ACL algorithms have been ported to SQL and to relational database systems.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Many "modern" (2000s and 2010s) SQL-based systems, like enterprise resource planning and content management systems, have used ACL models in their administration modules.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] In 2024, schema-indexed ACL models emerged as a lightweight alternative to traditional JSON-based permission storage.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] One notable proposal introduced the idea of storing only the indexes of allowed operations, rather than full permission trees.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] This technique, later formalized as *SCode ACL*, allows compact encoding of access rights (e.g., `"0 2 5"`) based on a predefined flattened schema, making it particularly efficient for use in stateless systems such as JWT tokens or session cookies.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] The approach gained early traction in developer communities for its minimalism and performance, and has since been adopted in both small-scale and production-grade systems.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] The main alternative to the ACL model is the role-based access-control (RBAC) model.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] A "minimal RBAC model", *RBACm*, can be compared with an ACL mechanism, *ACLg*, where only groups are permitted as entries in the ACL.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] Barkley (1997) showed that *RBACm* and *ACLg* are equivalent.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] In modern SQL implementations, ACLs also manage groups and inheritance in a hierarchy of groups.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] So "modern ACLs" can express all that RBAC express and are notably powerful (compared to "old ACLs") in their ability to express access-control policy in terms of the way in which administrators view organizations.
[src:cedar-policy/access-control-list] For data interchange, and for "high-level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC is a method of implementing access control policies that is highly adaptable and can be customized using a wide range of attributes, making it suitable for use in distributed or rapidly changing environments.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The only limitations on the policies that can be implemented with ABAC are the capabilities of the computational language and the availability of relevant attributes.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC policy rules are generated as Boolean functions of the subject's attributes, the object's attributes, and the environment attributes.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Unlike role-based access control (RBAC), which defines roles that carry a specific set of privileges associated with them and to which subjects are assigned, ABAC can express complex rule sets that can evaluate many different attributes.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Through defining consistent subject and object attributes into security policies, ABAC eliminates the need for explicit authorizations to individuals’ subjects needed in a non-ABAC access method, reducing the complexity of managing access lists and groups.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute values can be set-valued or atomic-valued.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Set-valued attributes contain more than one atomic value.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Atomic-valued attributes contain only one atomic value.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Examples are *clearance* and *sensitivity*.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be compared to static values or to one another, thus enabling relation-based access control.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control is sometimes referred to as **policy-based access control** (**PBAC**) or **claims-based access control** (**CBAC**), which is a Microsoft-specific term.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The key standards that implement ABAC are XACML and ALFA (XACML).
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP or Policy Decision Point is the brain of the architecture.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is the piece which evaluates incoming requests against policies it has been configured with.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The PIP or Policy Information Point bridges the PDP to external sources of attributes e.g.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be about anything and anyone.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies are statements that bring together attributes to express what can happen and is not allowed.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies in ABAC can be granting or denying policies.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies can also be local or global and can be written in a way that they override other policies.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] With ABAC you can have an unlimited number of policies that cater to many different scenarios and technologies.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Historically, access control models have included mandatory access control (MAC), discretionary access control (DAC), and more recently role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] These access control models are user-centric and do not take into account additional parameters such as resource information, the relationship between the user (the requesting entity) and the resource, and dynamic information, e.g. time of the day or user IP.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC tries to address this by defining access control based on attributes which describe the requesting entity (the user), the targeted object or resource, the desired action (view, edit, delete), and environmental or contextual information.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is why access control is said to be attribute-based.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] XACML, the eXtensible Access Control Markup Language, defines an architecture (shared with ALFA and NGAC), a policy language, and a request/response scheme.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] It does not handle attribute management (user attribute assignment, object attribute assignment, environment attribute assignment) which is left to traditional IAM tools, databases, and directories.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Companies, including every branch in the United States military, have started using ABAC.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] At a basic level, ABAC protects data with 'IF/THEN/AND' rules rather than assign data to users.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The US Department of Commerce has made this a mandatory practice and the adoption is spreading throughout several governmental and military agencies.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The concept of ABAC can be applied at any level of the technology stack and an enterprise infrastructure.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] For example, ABAC can be used at the firewall, server, application, database, and data layer.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The use of attributes bring additional context to evaluate the legitimacy of any request for access and inform the decision to grant or deny access.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] An important consideration when evaluating ABAC solutions is to understand its potential overhead on performance and its impact on the user experience.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] It is expected that the more granular the controls, the higher the overhead.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC can be used to apply attribute-based, fine-grained authorization to the API methods or functions.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] For instance, a banking API may expose an `approveTransaction(transId)` method.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The API receives the call and authenticates the user.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP retrieves the ABAC policy and necessary attributes.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] If the decision is Permit, the underlying API business logic is called.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Otherwise the API returns an error or access denied.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] One of the key benefits to ABAC is that the authorization policies and attributes can be defined in a technology neutral way.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This means policies defined for APIs or databases can be reused in the application space.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The same process and flow as the one described in the API section applies here too.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Security for databases has long been specific to the database vendors: Oracle VPD, IBM FGAC, and Microsoft RLS are all means to achieve fine-grained ABAC-like security.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Data security typically goes one step further than database security and applies control directly to the data element.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is often referred to as data-centric security.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] On traditional relational databases, ABAC policies can control access to data at the table, column, field, cell and sub-cell using logical controls with filtering conditions and masking based on attributes.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be data, user, session or tools based to deliver the greatest level of flexibility in dynamically granting/denying access to a specific data element.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] On big data, and distributed file systems such as Hadoop, ABAC applied at the data layer control access to folder, sub-folder, file, sub-file and other granular.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control can also be applied to Big Data systems like Hadoop.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies similar to those used previously can be applied when retrieving data from data lakes.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] As of Windows Server 2012, Microsoft has implemented an ABAC approach to controlling access to files and folders.
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is achieved through dynamic access control (DAC) and Security Descriptor Definition Language (SDDL).
[src:cedar-policy/attribute-based-access-control] SDDL can be seen as an ABAC language as it uses metadata of the user (claims) and of the file/ folder to control access.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Authorization is closely related to access control, which is what enforces the authorization policy by deciding whether access requests to resources from (authenticated) consumers shall be approved (granted) or disapproved (rejected).
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Authorization should not be confused with authentication, which is the process of verifying someone's identity.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Hence, access control in computer systems and networks relies on access authorization specified during configuration.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Authorization is the responsibility of an authority, such as a department manager, within the application domain, but is often delegated to a custodian such as a system administrator.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Authorizations are expressed as access policies in some types of "policy definition application", e.g. in the form of an access control list or a capability, or a policy administration point e.g.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Broken authorization is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] "Anonymous consumers" or "guests", are consumers that have not been required to authenticate.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] On a distributed system, it is often desirable to grant access without requiring a unique identity.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Familiar examples of access tokens include keys, certificates and tickets: they grant access without proving identity.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] A widely used framework for authorizing applications is OAuth 2.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] It provides a standardized way for third-party applications to obtain limited access to a user's resources without exposing their credentials.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] In modern systems, a widely used model for authorization is role-based access control (RBAC) where authorization is defined by granting subjects one or more roles, and then checking that the resource being accessed has been assigned at least one of those roles.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] However, with the rise of social media, Relationship-based access control is gaining more prominence.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Even when access is controlled through a combination of authentication and access control lists, the problems of maintaining the authorization data is not trivial, and often represents as much administrative burden as managing authentication credentials.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] It is often necessary to change or remove a user's authorization: this is done by changing or deleting the corresponding access rules on the system.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] Using atomic authorization is an alternative to per-system authorization management, where a trusted third party securely distributes authorization information.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] In public policy, authorization is a feature of trusted systems used for security or social control.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] In banking, an authorization is a hold placed on a customer's account when a purchase is made using a debit card or credit card.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] In publishing, sometimes public lectures and other freely available texts are published without the approval of the author.
[src:cedar-policy/authorization] An example is the 2002 *'The Theory of Everything: The Origin and Fate of the Universe'*, which was collected from Stephen Hawking's lectures and published without his permission as per copyright law.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] This guide is a reference for Version 4.5 of the Cedar policy language.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar is a language for writing authorization policies and making authorization decisions based on those policies.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] When you create an application, you need to ensure that only authorized users can access the application, and can do only what each user is authorized to do.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Using Cedar, you can decouple your business logic from the authorization logic.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] In your application’s code, you preface requests made to your operations with a call to Cedar’s authorization engine, asking “Is this request authorized?”.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Then, the application can either perform the requested operation if the decision is “allow”, or return an error message if the decision is “deny”.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] In addition to supporting the authorization requirements for your own custom applications directly, Cedar is the policy language for several authorization services.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] These services take the separation of business logic and authorization logic one step further: The services host the Cedar policies, and provide APIs for managing those policies and carrying out authorization decisions on behalf of all of your applications.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] They handle the heavy lifting so your applications don’t have to.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar evaluates each request against the provided policies and entities to make an allow or deny decision.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] The policies are completely separate from your application’s code.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] This design ensures that your security team can update permissions for your application without having to touch the application’s code.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] If you have multiple teams owning multiple backends, you can update your policies without needing to coordinate the updates across teams.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] A change to a policy can result in an immediate change in the logic used to authorize requests.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Separating the authorization model from your application code makes it easier to test.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar is analyzable, meaning it can be easily read and understood by new team members.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar provides several important features.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar policies are written as rules that specify the conditions under which access to resources is to be allowed or denied.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Policies include conditions that evaluate the attributes of the principal, the resource being accessed, and the context of the request.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar policies can use attributes, which are key-value pairs that represent various aspects of the principal, the resource, and the context of the request.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Attributes can include information such as user roles, resource types, time of day, location, and any other relevant contextual information.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar is a simple yet expressive language that is designed to support common authorization use cases, such as role-based access control (RBAC) and attribute-based access control (ABAC).
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] The language supports logical operators such as AND, OR, and NOT on Boolean values, in addition to common operators on other types, such as comparison operators on integers.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] This broad set of operators helps provide fine-grained control over access decisions.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] The Cedar evaluation engine evaluates policies dynamically.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] This design supports making changes in access control requirements that take effect immediately, and without requiring system-wide updates or downtime.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] This approach helps you to quickly and easily adapt to changing business rules or environmental conditions.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] The policy structure allows your policies to be indexed for quick retrieval.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] The design also supports fast, scalable, real-time evaluation with bounded latency.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Cedar policies are designed to be easy to read and understand, making them accessible to both technical and non-technical stakeholders involved in defining access control policies.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] This helps facilitate collaboration and communication among different stakeholders in a distributed system.
[src:cedar-policy/docs-cedarpolicy-com] Amazon Verified Permissions is a managed service using Cedar.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] In information security, **role-based access control** (**RBAC**) or **role-based security** is an approach to restricting system access to authorized users.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] It is a policy-neutral computer access control mechanism defined around roles and privileges.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] The components of RBAC, such as role-permissions, user-role and role-role relationships, make it simple to perform user assignments.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] RBAC can be used to facilitate administration of security in large organizations with hundreds of users and thousands of permissions.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Although RBAC is different from mandatory access control and discretionary access control (DAC) frameworks, it can enforce these policies.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Its approach is also different from context-based access control and access-control lists.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control and relationship-based access control are models that build on the concept of RBAC.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] A 1990s study by NIST demonstrated that RBAC addresses many needs of commercial and government organizations.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] RBAC is still commonly considered a best practice in information security management, including in implementation of information security standards related to access control.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Within an organization, roles are created for various job functions.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] The permissions to perform certain operations are assigned to specific roles.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Role authorization: A subject's active role must be authorized for the subject.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] With rule 1 above, this rule ensures that users can take on only roles for which they are authorized.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Permission authorization: A subject can exercise a permission only if the permission is authorized for the subject's active role.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] With rules 1 and 2, this rule ensures that users can exercise only permissions for which they are authorized.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Additional constraints may be applied as well, and roles can be combined in a hierarchy where higher-level roles subsume permissions owned by sub-roles.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] With the concepts of role hierarchy and constraints, one can control RBAC to create or simulate lattice-based access control (LBAC).
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Thus RBAC can be considered to be a superset of LBAC.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] A constraint places a restrictive rule on the potential inheritance of permissions from opposing roles.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Thus it can be used to achieve appropriate separation of duties.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] For example, the same person should not be allowed to both create a login account and to authorize the account creation.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] A subject may have *multiple* simultaneous sessions with/in different roles.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] RBAC is a flexible access control technology whose flexibility allows it to implement or discretionary access control (DAC) or mandatory access control (MAC).
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] DAC with groups (e.g., as implemented in POSIX file systems) can emulate RBAC.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] MAC can simulate RBAC if the role graph is restricted to a tree rather than a partially ordered set.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Prior to the development of RBAC, the Bell-LaPadula (BLP) model was synonymous with MAC, and file system permissions were synonymous with DAC.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] These were considered to be the only known models for access control: if a model was not BLP, it was considered to be a DAC model, and vice versa.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Research in the late 1990s demonstrated that RBAC falls in neither category.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Unlike context-based access control (CBAC), RBAC does not look at the message context (such as a connection's source).
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] RBAC has also been criticized for leading to role explosion, a problem in large enterprise systems which require access control of finer granularity than what RBAC can provide as roles are inherently assigned to operations and data types.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] In resemblance to CBAC, an Entity-Relationship Based Access Control system is able to secure instances of data by considering their association to the executing subject.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Access control lists (ACLs) are used in traditional discretionary access-control (DAC) systems to affect low-level data-objects.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] RBAC differs from ACL in assigning permissions to operations which change the direct-relations between several entities (see: *ACLg* below).
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] For example, an ACL could be used for granting or denying write access to a particular system file, but it wouldn't dictate how that file could be changed.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] In an RBAC-based system, an operation might be to 'create a credit account' transaction in a financial application or to 'populate a blood sugar level test' record in a medical application.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] A Role is thus a sequence of operations within a larger activity.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] RBAC has been shown to be particularly well suited to separation of duties (SoD) requirements, which ensure that two or more people must be involved in authorizing critical operations.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Necessary and sufficient conditions for safety of SoD in RBAC have been analyzed.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] An underlying principle of SoD is that no individual should be able to effect a breach of security through dual privilege.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] By extension, no person may hold a role that exercises audit, control or review authority over another, concurrently held role.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] For data interchange, and for "high level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control (ABAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC to consider additional attributes in addition to roles and groups.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] ABAC is policy-based in the sense that it uses policies rather than static permissions to define what is allowed or what is not allowed.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] In ReBAC, a subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] The advantage of this model is that allows for fine-grained permissions; for example, in a social network where users can share posts with other specific users.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] The use of RBAC to manage user privileges (computer permissions) within a single system or application is widely accepted as a best practice.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] A 2010 report prepared for NIST by the Research Triangle Institute analyzed the economic value of RBAC for enterprises and estimated benefits per employee from reduced employee downtime, more efficient provisioning, and more efficient access control policy administration.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] In an organization with a heterogeneous IT infrastructure and requirements that span dozens or hundreds of systems and applications, using RBAC to manage sufficient roles and assign adequate role memberships becomes extremely complex without hierarchical creation of roles and privilege assignments.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Newer systems extend the older NIST RBAC model to address the limitations of RBAC for enterprise-wide deployments.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] The NIST model was adopted as a standard by INCITS as ANSI/INCITS 359-2004.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] A discussion of some of the design choices for the NIST model has also been published.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] NIST Special Publication 800-53, an information security standard used by U.S. federal agencies and other organizations, includes role-based access control in its Access Enforcement controls under AC-3(7).
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Implementations of the CIS Controls, a set of best practices, often incorporate role-based access control as part of fulfilling Control 6, Access Control Management.
[src:cedar-policy/role-based-access-control] Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) regulations require implementation of access control as part of technical safeguards for electronic protected health information (45 CFR 164.312), and role-based access control is a typical approach in the industry.
